    <p>The Museu de les Ciències Príncipe Felipe is an interactive science and technology museum in Valencia's City of Arts and Sciences complex (Ciutat de les Arts i les Ciències), at Av. del Professor López Piñero, 7. The building was designed by Valencian architect Santiago Calatrava and spans 42,000 square metres of built surface, of which 26,000 square metres are exhibition space — the largest science museum building in Spain. The structure's biomorphic form, resembling a whale skeleton, is integrated with 13,500 square metres of surrounding reflecting pools.</p>
    <p>The museum opened in November 2000 and is operated by the Fundació de la Comunitat Valenciana Ciutat de les Arts i les Ciències. Its permanent exhibitions cover science, technology, and the environment across four floors, with interactive modules on topics including genetics, space exploration, physics, and ecology. The museum's stated principle — "forbidden not to touch, not to feel, and not to think" — reflects its hands-on approach. In 2025 the museum hosted the temporary exhibition "Leonardo da Vinci: 500 Years of Genius," running through early 2026, as part of the museum's 25th anniversary programme.</p>
    <p>The museum is part of a complex that also includes the Hemisfèric (IMAX dome cinema), the Oceanogràfic (Europe's largest aquarium), the Palau de les Arts opera house, and the L'Umbracle garden. Combo tickets covering multiple venues are sold exclusively through cac.es. The ticket office closes one hour before the museum. Audio guides cost €1 and are downloaded via mobile in six languages. Last updated: March 2026 · Verified</p>
